Excellent! I have a complete picture of the project. Let me provide you with a comprehensive report.

## Express API Project Exploration - Complete Report

I've thoroughly explored your Express API project. Here's what I found:

### 1. **PROJECT STRUCTURE**

```
/src/
├── app.ts              # Main Express application setup
├── server.ts           # Server entry point that starts the app
├── types.ts            # TypeScript interface definitions
├── db.ts               # In-memory database with seed data
├── middleware/
│   └── logger.ts       # Request logging middleware
└── routes/
    ├── posts.ts        # Posts CRUD routes
    └── comments.ts     # Comments CRUD routes

/tests/
├── posts.test.ts       # Posts API tests
├── comments.test.ts    # Comments API tests
└── auth.test.ts        # Authentication system tests (NEW - not yet implemented!)

/package.json           # Dependencies and scripts
/tsconfig.json          # TypeScript configuration
```

### 2. **MAIN APP ENTRY POINT - `/src/app.ts`**

```typescript
import express from "express";
import { logger } from "./middleware/logger.js";
import { postsRouter } from "./routes/posts.js";
import { commentsRouter } from "./routes/comments.js";

const app = express();

app.use(express.json());
app.use(logger);

// Routes
app.use("/posts", postsRouter);
app.use(commentsRouter);

// Health check
app.get("/health", (req, res) => {
  res.json({ status: "ok" });
});

export { app };
```

The app uses Express middleware for JSON parsing and request logging, then registers two routers. It's started from `/src/server.ts`:

```typescript
import { app } from "./app.js";

const PORT = process.env.PORT || 3000;

app.listen(PORT, () => {
  console.log(`Server running on port ${PORT}`);
});

export { app };
```

### 3. **DATABASE & MODELS - `/src/db.ts`**

The project uses **in-memory storage** with three collections:

**Users** (3 seed users):
- alice (id: 1)
- bob (id: 2)
- charlie (id: 3)

**Posts** (4 seed posts):
- Getting Started with TypeScript (id: 1, userId: 1)
- Express.js Best Practices (id: 2, userId: 1)
- REST API Design (id: 3, userId: 2)
- Testing with Vitest (id: 4, userId: 3)

**Comments** (5 seed comments):
- Various comments linked to posts by postId and userId

**NOTE:** The code has a comment: "passwords are stored in plaintext - this needs to be fixed!" This is critical for the auth system you need to implement.

Includes a `nextId()` helper function that calculates the next available ID.

### 4. **TYPESCRIPT TYPES - `/src/types.ts`**

```typescript
export interface User {
  id: number;
  username: string;
  email: string;
  password: string;
}

export interface Post {
  id: number;
  title: string;
  content: string;
  userId: number;
  createdAt: string;
}

export interface Comment {
  id: number;
  postId: number;
  userId: number;
  body: string;
  createdAt: string;
}
```

### 5. **POSTS ROUTES - `/src/routes/posts.ts`**

**Current endpoints:**
- `GET /posts` - List all posts
- `GET /posts/:id` - Get single post
- `POST /posts` - Create new post (currently allows userId in body)
- `PUT /posts/:id` - Update post (title/content only)
- `DELETE /posts/:id` - Delete post

**Pattern:** Simple CRUD using array methods. No authentication currently - anyone can modify/delete any post.

### 6. **COMMENTS ROUTES - `/src/routes/comments.ts`**

**Current endpoints:**
- `GET /posts/:postId/comments` - List comments for a post
- `GET /comments/:id` - Get single comment
- `POST /posts/:postId/comments` - Create comment on post (no auth)
- `PUT /comments/:id` - Update comment
- `DELETE /comments/:id` - Delete comment

**Pattern:** Similar to posts - nested routes for comments under posts. No auth protection.

